    <svcsubproc>
        <title>Drive Pinion - Assembly</title>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Initial Assembly</emph>
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using a suitable driver, press the inner pinion bearing onto the pinion.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a101" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1969A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press the inner and outer pinion bearing cups into the carrier until seated.</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Use a 0.0381 mm (0.0015 in) feeler gauge to verify the bearing cups have completely seated in
                        the bearing bores.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Lubricate the bearing cups and cone.</para>
                    <randlist type="dash">
                        <item>
                            <para>Use SAE 75W-140 High Performance Rear Axle Lubricant or equivalent.</para>
                        </item>
                    </randlist>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a102" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1967A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Seat the outer pinion bearing on the pinion.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a103" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/n0020651.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="352px"/>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Seat the inner pinion bearing into the cup by positioning a 152.4 x 152.4 x
                    152.4-mm (6 x 6 x 6-inch) block of wood under the pinion.
                </callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Place the original pinion preload spacer onto the pinion.</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Place the outer pinion bearing onto the pinion.</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Using a suitable press, seat the outer bearing on the pinion.</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Do not install the pinion seal at this time.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the pinion flange.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the pinion nut.</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Using a suitable torque multiplier, tighten the pinion nut.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Tighten to 1128 Nm (832 lb-ft).</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a104" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1961A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Measuring pinion bearing preload torque</emph>
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure the torque to rotate.</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Take torque measurements every fourth revolution.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Proceed to Pinion bearing preload adjustment in this procedure if the bearing preload torque
                        is not within the specifications. Proceed to Final assembly in this procedure if the bearing
                        preload torque is within the specifications.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a105" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/n0023958.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Pinion bearing preload adjustment</emph>
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Also refer to the following illustration.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Adjust the pinion bearing preload by installing a new pinion bearing preload spacer.</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>To increase the preload, install a thinner spacer. To decrease the preload, install a thicker
                        spacer.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>The pinion bearing preload spacers are available in sizes from 7.26 to 8.00 mm (0.286 to 0.315
                        inch).
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Always measure the new spacer before installing it.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>On a flat surface, sand the next thicker size spacer with emery cloth to the required
                        thickness to obtain a closer adjustment. Thoroughly wash the spacer to remove the emery cuttings
                        before installation.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>A 0.0254 mm (0.001 inch) change in the spacer thickness will change the torque rate
                        approximately 3.3894 Nm (30 lb-in).
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Repeat Measuring pinion bearing preload torque and Pinion bearing preload adjustment in this
                        procedure until the rotational torque is within specifications.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a106" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1974A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="352px"/>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f0502a107" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/n0023958.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Final Assembly</emph>
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using a suitable torque multiplier, remove the pinion nut.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a108" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1961A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Hammering on the pinion flange will close in the bearing bores and misalign the flange lugs. This
                    will result in premature failure of the journal needle bearings. Serious damage will also occur
                    internally to the differential ring gear and pinion or pinion bearings by hammering on external
                    components. Remove and install the pinion flange using only the procedures in this section.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using the special tool, remove the pinion flange.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a109" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/n0020650.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using the special tool, install the pinion seal.</para>
            <para>&#8226; A rotational torque of 1.6947-5.0841 Nm (15-45 lb-in) is acceptable with the pinion seal
                installed.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a110" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../fign00/n0020653.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the pinion flange.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply Stud and Bearing Mount to the pinion threads and install a new pinion nut. Using a
                suitable torque multiplier, tighten the nut.
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Tighten to 1128 Nm (832 lb-ft).</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Use Stud and Bearing Mount TA-27 or equivalent.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0502a111" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figDE1/DE1961A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="232px"/>
        </figure>
